{"title_page": "Greg Rust", "text_new": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Greg Rust\n| image       =\n| birthname   = Gregory Paul Rust\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1970|7|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n| employer    = [[V8 Supercars|V8 Supercars Media]]<br />[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]]\n| nationality = Australian\n}}\n'''Gregory Paul Rust'''<ref>{{cite podcast|url=https://www.v8sleuth.com.au/greg-rust-v8-sleuth-podcast/|title=Greg Rust, Part 1|minutes=3:24|website=V8 Sleuth Podcast|date=8 April 2020}}</ref> (born 19 July 1970 in [[Sydney]]) is an [[Australia]]n [[motor racing]] presenter and commentator for the [[V8 Supercars]] championship. He has previously worked for [[Network Ten]], the [[Nine Network]]<ref name=\"smarttalk.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smarttalk.com.au/greg-rust-media.shtml|title=Greg Rust Media Bio|publisher=Smart Talk Promotions}}</ref> and the [[Special Broadcasting Service]]<ref name=\"smarttalk.com.au\"/> (SBS) as a freelance commentator/reporter/presenter, mainly covering motor racing.\n\nHe is colloquially known as \"Rusty\" or \"Thrusta\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gregrust.com.au/about/ |title=About |publisher=Greg Rust |accessdate=2016-09-10}}</ref> (a nickname given to him by the late [[Barry Sheene]] a former World Motorcycle Champion and Network Ten colleague).<ref name=\"NetworkTenPage\">{{cite web|url=http://ten.com.au/one-hd-greg-rust.htm|title=Greg Rust Bio on Network Ten|publisher=Network Ten}}</ref>\n\n==Radio career==\nRust worked for three years with the [[Macquarie Radio Network]] stations [[2GB]] and [[2CH]] in Sydney initially as a sport reporter and later became a daytime news reader.<ref name=\"NetworkTenPage\"/>\n\n==Television career==\n===Early years===\nAfter cutting his teeth with SBS motorsport program ''Speedweek'', Rust was drafted into Channel 9's commentary team for the final Australian Motorcycle Grand Prix at the [[Eastern Creek Raceway]] in 1996. He called the support races with [[1980 Formula One season|1980]] [[Formula One]] World Champion [[Alan Jones (racing driver)|Alan Jones]].\n\n===Network Ten===\nIn 1997 he was hired by Ten to host the [[Australian Super Touring Championship]] for 2-litre Touring Cars - a position previously held by his close friend [[Leigh Diffey]], who had moved on to Network Ten's [[V8 Supercar]] coverage.  Rust commentated the Australian Super Touring Championship for 2 years before starting work as V8 pit reporter late in 1998. He was a part of Ten's V8 coverage for almost 10 years - even hosting and anchoring the commentary on occasions.  During this period the station won numerous [[Logie Award]]s for its broadcast of the famous [[Bathurst 1000]] and Rust developed a reputation as a pit specialist also working on the [[Gold Coast Indy 300]] and the [[Australian Grand Prix]] in Melbourne. Despite an offer to join the [[Seven Network]] in 2007, Rust stayed with Ten to front the station's [[MotoGP]] and F1 broadcasts and its long running magazine motorsport show ''[[RPM (TV series)|RPM]]''.  He also hosted and commentated Ten's coverage of the [[Red Bull Air Race]] series.\n\nRust also worked on [[One (Australian TV channel)|One]]'s coverage of the [[2014 Winter Olympics]].<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/tv/channel-10-promises-more-than-550-hours-of-sochi-winter-olympics-coverage/story-e6frfmyi-1226749280353 Channel 10 promises more than 500 hours of Sochi Winter Olympics coverage], ''News.com.au'' 30 October 2013</ref> and the Glasgow Commonwealth Games<ref>{{cite web|url=http://irun.org.au/Events/Athletics-Australia/commonwealth-games-1 |title=Commonwealth Games |website=Irun.org.au |date=2014-04-14 |accessdate=2016-09-10}}</ref>\n\n===V8 Media and Fox Sports===\nIn 2015, the V8 Supercars television rights moved to a shared broadcast between Fox Sports and Network Ten.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/motor-sports/v8-supercars/v8-supercars-signs-241m-media-rights-deal-with-fox-sports-foxtel-and-ten-network-from-2015/story-fn2ms9um-1226785594801 | title=V8 Supercars signs $241m media rights deal with FOX SPORTS, Foxtel and Ten Network from 2015 | work=[[Fox Sports Australia]] | date=18 December 2013 | accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> The broadcast shared a common commentary team, produced by V8 Supercars Media and headed up by Rust and [[Neil Crompton]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.v8supercars.com.au/news/championship/v8-supercars-commentary-team-revealed | title=V8 Supercars commentary team revealed | work=V8Supercars.com.au | date=6 February 2015 | accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> Rust also began hosting Fox Sports' new V8 Supercars panel series \u2018\u2019[[Inside Supercars]]\u2019\u2019.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.v8supercars.com.au/news/championship/inside-supercars-debuts-this-evening | title=Inside Supercars debuts this evening  | work=[[V8 Supercars]] | date=3 March 2015 | accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> He fronts the coverage for various international networks and in 2016 made a return to pit reporting for the races.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supercars.com/news/championship/mark-skaife-joins-v8-supercars-commentary-line-up/ |title=Mark Skaife joins V8 Supercars commentary line-up |publisher=Supercars |accessdate=2016-09-10}}</ref> He currently commentates the [[Super2 Series]], with four time [[Bathurst 1000]] winner [[Greg Murphy]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn into a family with a genuine love for all forms of motorsport, he was a regular at the [[Sydney Showground Speedway]] as a child, and competed as an amateur racer who started out in [[karts]]. In his late teens and early twenties, Rust enjoyed some class wins as a driver in rallysprints and khana-crosses.  He has also driven [[V8 Supercars]], [[Formula Holden]], [[Formula Ford]], [[Toyota Racing Series]] and [[Midget car racing|Speedcars/Midgets]] for story research.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://ten.com.au/one-hd-greg-rust.htm Ten.com.au]\n* [http://www.v8x.com.au/cms/A_30145/article.html V8x.com.au]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070828231537/http://parramattacityraceway.com.au/release.asp?NewsId=23365 Parramattacityraceway.com.au]\n* [http://www.smarttalk.com.au/ Smarttalk.com.au/]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[RPM (TV series)|RPM]]'' <br> Host |before=[[Bill Woods]]|after=[[Matthew White (journalist)|Matthew White]]|years=2007\u201308, 2011}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[Inside Supercars]]'' <br> Host |before=program started|after=incumbent|years=2015\u2013}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rust, Greg}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian sports broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Motorsport announcers]]\n[[Category:Australian television presenters]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=November 2010}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Gregory Rust\n| image       =\n| birthname   = Gregory Paul Rust\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1970|7|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n| employer    = [[V8 Supercars|V8 Supercars Media]]<br />[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]]\n| nationality = Australian\n}}\n'''Gregory Paul Rust'''<ref>{{cite podcast|url=https://www.v8sleuth.com.au/greg-rust-v8-sleuth-podcast/|title=Greg Rust, Part 1|minutes=3:24|website=V8 Sleuth Podcast|date=8 April 2020}}</ref> (born 19 July 1970 in [[Sydney]]) is an [[Australia]]n [[motor racing]] presenter and commentator for the [[V8 Supercars]] championship. He has previously worked for [[Network Ten]], the [[Nine Network]]<ref name=\"smarttalk.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smarttalk.com.au/greg-rust-media.shtml|title=Greg Rust Media Bio|publisher=Smart Talk Promotions}}</ref> and the [[Special Broa