ch 2015 | accessdate=9 November 2015}}</ref> He fronts the coverage for various international networks and in 2016 made a return to pit reporting for the races.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supercars.com/news/championship/mark-skaife-joins-v8-supercars-commentary-line-up/ |title=Mark Skaife joins V8 Supercars commentary line-up |publisher=Supercars |accessdate=2016-09-10}}</ref> He currently commentates the [[Super2 Series]], with four time [[Bathurst 1000]] winner [[Greg Murphy]].\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn into a family with a genuine love for all forms of motorsport, he was a regular at the [[Sydney Showground Speedway]] as a child, and competed as an amateur racer who started out in [[karts]]. In his late teens and early twenties, Rust enjoyed some class wins as a driver in rallysprints and khana-crosses.  He has also driven [[V8 Supercars]], [[Formula Holden]], [[Formula Ford]], [[Toyota Racing Series]] and [[Midget car racing|Speedcars/Midgets]] for story research.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://ten.com.au/one-hd-greg-rust.htm Ten.com.au]\n* [http://www.v8x.com.au/cms/A_30145/article.html V8x.com.au]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070828231537/http://parramattacityraceway.com.au/release.asp?NewsId=23365 Parramattacityraceway.com.au]\n* [http://www.smarttalk.com.au/ Smarttalk.com.au/]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[RPM (TV series)|RPM]]'' <br> Host |before=[[Bill Woods]]|after=[[Matthew White (journalist)|Matthew White]]|years=2007\u201308, 2011}}\n{{succession box|title=''[[Inside Supercars]]'' <br> Host |before=program started|after=incumbent|years=2015\u2013}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rust, Greg}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian sports broadcasters]]\n[[Category:Motorsport announcers]]\n[[Category:Australian television presenters]]\n", "name_user": "Bart-16", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greg_Rust"}
{"title_page": "Crime in Washington", "text_new": "This article refers to [[crime]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Washington (state)|Washington]].{{Infobox Uniform Crime Reports|city_name=Washington|year=2018|robbery=73.9|aggravated_assault=189.1|violent_crime=311.5|burglary=533.5|larceny_theft=2045.4|motor_vehicle_theft=367.3|property_crime=2946.2|source_name=FBI UCS Annual Crime Reports 2018|source_url=http://www.disastercenter.com/crime/wacrime.htm}}\n\n== History of Crime ==\nThe following table displays the number of crimes for every decade from 1960 to 2010. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"8\" |Number of crimes in Washington from 1960-2010 (Every decade)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.disastercenter.com/crime/wacrime.htm|title=Washington Crime Rates 1960 - 2018|website=www.disastercenter.com|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |\n! colspan=\"3\" |Violent\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Theft\n|-\n!Year\n!Population\n!Violent\n!Murder\n!Aggravated Assault\n!Property\n!Larceny-Theft\n!Vehicle Theft\n|-\n|1960\n|2,853,214\n|1,616\n|61\n|503\n|62,072\n|43,657\n|4,507\n|-\n|1970\n|3,409,169\n|7,546\n|120\n|3,624\n|158,858\n|97,279\n|12,335\n|-\n|1980\n|4,113,331\n|19,098\n|225\n|11,146\n|265,338\n|172,468\n|16,272\n|-\n|1990\n|4,866,692\n|24,410\n|238\n|14,731\n|278,440\n|195,221\n|21,759\n|-\n|2000\n|5,894,121\n|21,788\n|196\n|13,043\n|279,144\n|190,650\n|35,018\n|-\n|2010\n|6,742,950\n|21,138\n|154\n|12,476\n|249,426\n|168,490\n|25,744\n|}\n\n=== 1960 ===\nIn 1960, the population of Washington was 2,853,214 people. About 68% of the population resided in urban areas, whereas the remaining 32% resided in rural areas. The largest age group of the population was the 5-11 age group with 576,525, followed by the 35-44 year age group with 385,900, then the 15-24 year olds with 383,926.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.historylink.org/File/9341|title=1960 census: First census to show full effects of post-World War II baby boom in Washington state; urban areas grow in population, rural areas contract.|website=www.historylink.org|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The total number of violent crimes that occurred in that year was 1,616. However this is a realtively small number compared to the population of that year. The majority of crimes were related to property, with a total figure of 62,072 which is approximately 2.1% of the population. The next biggest category was larceny-theft with 43,657 cases. Crimes classified as murder were relatively low with 61 cases.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n=== 1970 ===\nIn 1970, crimes from the previous year in each category increased drastically. The increase in population was by 555,955 people. Violent crime increased nearly 470%, rising to 7,546 cases. The biggest per case rise in crime was in property, with an increase of 96,786 cases.<ref name=\":0\" /> During this decade, although murder cases were the lowest of crimes reported under violent crimes, they had the highest percentage of arrests. Overall, the average amount of reported arrests per reported crimes for the decade was 19.82%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bjs.gov/content/pub/pdf/hca-sw7182.pdf|title=History of Crimes and Arrests: State of Washington 1971 to 1982|last=|first=|date=August 1983|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===== '''Notable Cases:''' =====\n\n*[[Ted Bundy]] (1946-1989): An American [[serial killer]] who was convicted of the murders of 30 people which took place between 1973-1978. He started his crimes in the state of Washington and committed a total of 11 his murders there.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Michaud|first=Stephen|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=rO5IdAhFw_YC&lpg=PA1&pg=PA1&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Only Living Witness: The True Story of Serial Sex Killer Ted Bundy|last2=Aynesworth|first2=Hugh|publisher=Authorlink Press|year=1999|isbn=1-928704-11-5|location=|pages=339}}</ref>\n\n=== 1980 ===\nThe population in 1980 rose by 704,162 from the last decade, a relatively larger amount compared to the increase from 1960 to 1970. Violent crimes rose to 19,098 cases. Murder also rose to 225 cases, a 87.5% increase from 1970. The category with the biggest increase in crime was again in property with a rise of 106,480 cases.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was believed that part of the continuing crime increases, which was carried on from the last decade, was widely due to soft policies towards parole release of criminals, poor treatment of prisoners and weak rehabilitation programs which all led to re-offending. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Zimring|first=Franklin|title=The Great American Crime Decline|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=28, 35}}</ref>\n\n===== Notable Cases: =====\n\n* [[Gary Ridgway]] (1949): An American serial killer who was convicted of 49 out of the 71 murders he confessed to. The majority of these murders were during the 1980s where the bodies of the victims were dumped at locations around Washington, notably at the [[Green River (Duwamish River tributary)|Green River]] and [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport|Seattle-Tacoma International Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://murderpedia.org/male.R/images/ridgway_gary/reports/summary.pdf|title=Prosector's Summary of the Evidence; Case No. 01-1-10270-9 SEA; State of Washington vs Gary Leon Ridgway|last=Maleng|first=Norm|date=2003-04-11|website=|location=King County Courthouse, Washington|page=3, 4, 42, 62|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n=== 1990 ===\nThe population rose by 753,361 people in 1990. However, despite the increase in population, increases in crime levels plummeted in most categories for the first time in 30 years since the 60s. The previously largest category of crime, property crime, had record breaking drops in the increases of cases. The number of cases for property crime was 278,440, only an increase of 13,302. This was a huge drop relative to the rise in cases in 1980 of 106,480 cases. Similarly notable drops were in the number of murders in the violent crime category, with only an increase of 13 cases.<ref name=\":0\" /> While there is no determinate cause as to what led to this significant drop in all levels of crime, it was widely believed that new and harsh law enforcement initiatives and policies led to the decrease in crime in not just the state of Washington, but across the United States.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Levitt|first=Stephen|date=Winter 2004|title=Understanding Why Crime Fell in the 1990s: Four Factors that Explain the Decline and Six that Do Not|url=https://pubs.aeaweb.org/doi/pdf/10.1257/089533004773563485|journal=Economic Perspectives|volume=18|pages=173 - 175|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> The introduction of new gun control laws and laws allowing concealed carry was also believed to cause this reduction in crime, however the lack of evidence towards these claims dismissed the belief.<ref name=\":2\" /> Additionally, there is also data to suggest that increase in taxpayer costs contributed to the decrease in crime rates through funding towards the criminal justice system in Washington. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:U2rncl70wAkJ:www.wsipp.wa.gov/ReportFile/1072/Wsipp_WSIPP-s-Benefit-Cost-Tool-for-States-Examining-Policy-Options-in-Sentencing-and-Corrections_Presentation-to-the-Senate-Human-Services-Corrections-Committee-January-21-2011.pptx+&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=au|title=Crime Trends, Good News, What Works, and Analyzing Options|last=Aos|first=Stephen|date=2011-01-21|website=webcache.googleusercontent.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nIn 2008, there were 268,624 crimes reported in Washington, including 193 murders.<ref name=wac>{{cite web|author=Christopher Effgen |url=http://www.disastercenter.com/crime/wacrime.htm |title=Washington Crime Rates 1960 - 2014 |publisher=Disastercenter.com |accessdate=2015-10-26}}</ref> In 2014, there were 281,842 crimes reported, including 174 murders.<ref name=wac/>\n==Capital punishment laws==\n{{Main|Capital punishment in Washington state}}\nSince October 11th 2018, [[Capital punishment]] is no longer applied in this state.<ref>http://www.religioustolerance.org/execut3.htm</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Law of Washington]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Washington}}\n{{CrimeUS}}\n\n[[Category:Crime in Washington (state)| ]]\n\n\n{{crime-stub}}\n{{Washington-stub}}\n", "text_old": "This article refers to [[crime]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Washington (state)|Washington]].{{Infobox Uniform Crime Reports|city_name=Washington|year=2018|robbery=73.9|aggravated_assault=189.1|violent_crime=311.5|burglary=533.5|larceny_theft=2045.4|motor_vehicle_theft=367.3|property_crime=2946.2|source_name=FBI UCS Annual Crime Reports 2018|source_url=http://www.disastercenter.com/crime/wacrime.htm}}\n\n== History of Crime ==\nThe following table displays the number of crimes for every decade from 1960 to 2010. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"8\" |Number of crimes in Washington from 1960-2010 (Every decade)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.disastercenter.com/crime/wacrime.htm|title=Washington Crime Rates 1960 - 2018|website=www.disastercenter.com|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |\n! colspan=\"3\" |Violent\n!\n! colspan=\"2\" |Theft\n|-\n!Year\n!Population\n!Violent\n!Murder\n!Aggravated Assault\n!Property\n!Larceny-Theft\n!Vehicle Theft\n|-\n|1960\n|2,853,214\n|1,616\n|61\n|503\n|62,072\n|43,657\n|4,507\n|-\n|1970\n|3,409,169\n|7,546\n|120\n|3,624\n|158,858\n|97,279\n|12,335\n|-\n|1980\n|4,113,331\n|19,098\n|225\n|11,146\n|265,338\n|172,468\n|16,272\n|-\n|1990\n|4,866,692\n|24,410\n|238\n|14,731\n|278,440\n|195,221\n|21,759\n|-\n|2000\n|5,894,121\n|21,788\n|196\n|13,043\n|279,144\n|190,650\n|35,018\n|-\n|2010\n|6,742,950\n|21,138\n|154\n|12,476\n|249,426\n|168,490\n|25,744\n|}\n\n=== 1960 ===\nIn 1960, the population of Washington was 2,853,214 people. About 68% of the population resided in urban areas, whereas the remaining 32% resided in rural areas. The largest age group of the population was the 5-11 age group with 576,525, followed by the 35-44 year age group with 385,900, then the 15-24 year olds with 383,926.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.historylink.org/File/9341|title=1960 census: First census to show full effects of post-World War II baby boom in Washington state; urban areas grow in population, rural areas contract.|website=www.historylink.org|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> The total number of violent crimes that occurred in that year was 1,616. However this is a realtively small number compared to the population of that year. The majority of crimes were related to property, with a total figure of 62,072 which is approximately 2.1% of the population. The next biggest category was larceny-theft with 43,657 cases. Crimes classified as murder were relatively low with 61 cases.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n=== 1970 ===\nIn 1970, crimes from the previous year in each category increased drastically. The increase in population was by 555,955 people. Violent crime increased nearly 470%, rising to 7,546 cases. The biggest per case rise in crime was in property, with an increase of 96,786 cases.<ref name=\":0\" /> During this decade, although murder cases were the lowest of crimes reported under violent crimes, they had the highest percentage of arrests. Overall, the average amount of reported arrests per reported crimes for the decade was 19.82%.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bjs.gov/content/pub/pdf/hca-sw7182.pdf|title=History of Crimes and Arrests: State of Washington 1971 to 1982|last=|first=|date=August 1983|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n===== '''Notable Cases:''' =====\n\n*The [[Ted Bundy]] murders (1946-1989): An American [[serial killer]] who was convicted of the murders of 30 people which took place between 1973-1978. He started his crimes in the state of Washington and committed a total of 11 his murders there.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Michaud|first=Stephen|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=rO5IdAhFw_YC&lpg=PA1&pg=PA1&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Only Living Witness: The True Story of Serial Sex Killer Ted Bundy|last2=Aynesworth|first2=Hugh|publisher=Authorlink Press|year=1999|isbn=1-928704-11-5|location=|pages=339}}</ref>\n\n=== 1980 ===\nThe population in 1980 rose by 704,162 from the last decade, a relatively larger amount compared to the increase from 1960 to 1970. Violent crimes rose to 19,098 cases. Murder also rose to 225 cases, a 87.5% increase from 1970. The category with the biggest increase in crime was again in property with a rise of 106,480 cases.<ref name=\":0\" /> It was believed that part of the continuing crime increases, which was carried on from the last decade, was widely due to soft policies towards parole release of criminals, poor treatment of prisoners and weak rehabilitation programs which all led to re-offending. <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=Zimring|first=Franklin|title=The Great American Crime Decline|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=28, 35}}</ref>\n\n===== Notable Cases: =====\n\n* [[Gary Ridgway]] (1949): An American serial killer who was convicted of 49 out of the 71 murders he confessed to. The majorty of these murders were during the 1980s where the bodies of the victims were dumped at locations around Washington, notably at the Green River and Seattle-Tacoma International Airport.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://murderpedia.org/male.R/images/ridgway_gary/reports/summary.pdf|title=Prosector's Summary of the Evidence; Case No. 01-1-10270-9 SEA; State of Washington vs Gary Leon Ridgway|last=Maleng|first=Norm|date=2003-04-11|website=|location=King County Courthouse, Washington|page=3, 4, 42, 62|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n=== 1990 ===\nThe population rose by 753,361 people in 1990. However, despite the increase in population, increases in crime levels plummeted in most categories for the first time in 30 years since the 60s. The previously largest category of crime, property crime, had record breaking drops in the increases of cases. The number of cases for property crime was 278,440, only an increase of 13,302. This was a huge drop relative to the rise in cases in 1980 of 106,480 cases. Similarly notable drops were in the number of murders in the violent crime category, with only an increase of 13 cases.<ref name=\":0\" /> While there is no determinate cause as to what led to this significant drop in all levels of crime, it was widely believed that new and harsh law enforcement initiatives and policies led to the decrease in crime in not just the state of Washington, but across the United States.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Levitt|first=Stephen|date=Winter 2004|title=Understanding Why Crime Fell in the 1990s: Four Factors that Explain the Decline and Six that Do Not|url=https://pubs.aeaweb.org/doi/pdf/10.1257/089533004773563485|journal=Economic Perspectives|volume=18|pages=173 - 175|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\" /> The introduction of new gun control laws and laws allowing concealed carry was also believed to cause this reduction in crime, however the lack of evidence towards these claims dismissed the belief.<ref name=\":2\" /> Additionally, there is also data to suggest that increase in taxpayer costs contributed to the decrease in crime rates through funding towards the criminal justice system in Washington. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:U2rncl70wAkJ:www.wsipp.wa.gov/ReportFile/1072/Wsipp_WSIPP-s-Benefit-Cost-Tool-for-States-Examining-Policy-Options-in-Sentencing-and-Corrections_Presentation-to-the-Senate-Human-Services-Corrections-Committee-January-21-2011.pptx+&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=au|title=Crime Trends, Good News, What Works, and Analyzing Options|last=Aos|first=Stephen|date=2011-01-21|website=webcache.googleusercontent.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nIn 2008, there were 268,624 crimes reported in Washington, including 193 murders.<ref name=wac>{{cite web|author=Christopher Effgen |url=http://www.disastercenter.com/crime/wacrime.htm |title=Washington Crime Rates 1960 - 2014 |publisher=Disastercenter.com |accessdate=2015-10-26}}</ref> In 2014, there were 281,842 crimes reported, including 174 murders.<ref name=wac/>\n==Capital punishment laws==\n{{Main|Capital punishment in Washington state}}\nSince October 11th 2018, [[Capital punishment]] is no longer applied in this state.<ref>http://www.religioustolerance.org/execut3.htm</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Law of Washington]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Washington}}\n{{CrimeUS}}\n\n[[Category:Crime in Washington (state)| ]]\n\n\n{{crime-stub}}\n{{Washington-stub}}\n", "name_user": "JPanda1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable Cases::added links to locations. standardised notable cases to the names of the killers before giving a description.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crime_in_Washington"}
{"title_page": "The Adventures of Noko Mashaba", "text_new": "{{short description|South Africa animated sociopolitical satire}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox television\n| image                        =\n| caption                      = ''The Adventures of Noko Mashaba'' introduction shot, featuring all five of the main characters of the show.\n| genre                        = [[Satire]]<br />Black comedy<br />2D Animation<br />Adventure\n| creator                      = [[Jonas Lekganyane]]\n| runtime                      = 5 - 15 minutes\n| company                      = Rams Comics (Pty) Ltd.\n| executive_producer           = Jonas Lekganyane\n| voices                       = Katisho Mogashoa<br />Joey Lekganyane<br />Nash Maoasha<br />Jonas Lekganyane<br />Sbusiso Cossa<br />Sylvester Mphahlele\n|theme_music_composer          = [[Jonas Lekganyane]]\n|opentheme                     = \"[[The adventure of Noko Mashaba Theme|''The Adventures of Noko Mashaba'' Theme]]\"\n|country                       = [[South Africa]]\n|language                      = Sepedi<br />English<br />Zulu<br />Tswana\n| website                      = http://www.nokomashaba.co.za\n}}\n\n'''''The Adventures of Noko Mashaba''''' is a [[South Africa]]n animated sociopolitical satire created by a self-taught animator and university dropout [[Jonas Lekganyane]] for [[Soweto TV]], [[Ekurhuleni TV]] and [[YouTube]]. Intended for any audience, the show is inspired by the American adult animated sitcom ''[[South Park]]'' and centers around a fictional character \u2013 Noko Mashaba \u2013 an ordinary guy hailing from the calm streets of Limpopo, who occasionally ventures on extraordinary adventures to unravel mysteries and relive urban legends. On the show Mashaba always finds himself in informative, controversial and attention-grabbing situations.\n\nThe series was created in early 2013 and premiered on [[YouTube]] with one episode called \"Noko & the Famous Venda Tree\" \u2013 an episode about a mythological tree from the deep ends of [[Venda]], South Africa, which supposedly extends men's penises if planted in the right manner. The series first went viral over the internet after the release of the episode called \"Noko in High School\". The show focuses on current affairs, corruption, celebrity scandals, urban legends, history and random humor.\n\nLekganyane developed the series in 2013 after being obliged to drop out of varsity due to financial difficulties. After a few months he started his own animation company called [[Rams Comics]]. The production company that produces the adventures of Noko Mashaba and other cartoon shows such as [[The Dons show]].\n\nAn episode of the show called \"Noko vs. [[Izikhothane]]\" was rated as the most watched YouTube video of the year by [[Google]] when it revealed the most watched videos of the year in South Africa 2014. In 2015 two of the episodes of the show made their way to Google's Top 10 most viewed YouTube videos in South Africa. The show has made a number of features on a number of South African television shows. In early 2014 the show made its debut TV feature on an [[E.tv|ETV]] show called ''Against All Odds'' with Mpho Lakage, which was a profiling interview about the creator [[Jonas Lekganyane]], followed by ''[[Mzansi insider]]'', ''[[100% Youth]]'' and ''[[Sunday Live]]'' on [[SABC]]. In 2015 Noko Mashaba won the South African Film, Art, Music & Entertainment award (FAME) for best comedian. In 2016 Rams Comics along with ''[[Supa Strikas]]'' shared the comic category award of the [[YouTube]] Sub-Saharan Africa Creator YouTube awards.\n\n==Premise==\n\n===Setting and characters===\n\nThe series features characters inspired by people that exist in real life and famous [[South Africa]]n personalities. It starts with a disclaimer similar to ''[[South Park]]''{{'}}s [[tongue-in-cheek]] disclaimer: \"All characters and events in the following clip\u2014even those based on real people\u2014are entirely fictional. All celebrity voices are impersonated... Poorly.\"\n\nThe show follows the intriguing life of a fictional character, '''Noko Mashaba'''. Mashaba is an audacious chap, well known for his humorous personality, created and voiced by [[Jonas Lekganyane]]. Noko was raised by his grandmother; his parents were political activist in the [[South African apartheid]] era. They disappeared with other activists into exile before their son could speak. Noko is in between jobs, in some episodes he is a Barbershop owner, some he is the president's right-hand man, but most of the time he appears as a cop.\n\nMashaba always has a sidekick with him, one of his sidekicks is '''Phusu''' \u2013 an intellectual Sangoma/wizard, who graduated at a fictional university called \"Loying University\" and obtained a degree in \"Loying Engineering\". Phusu combines the art of sorcery and science to solve the unsolvable, which makes him a remarkably exceptional [[Traditional healers of South Africa|Sangoma]].\n\nMashaba's second sidekick is '''Mthembu''' - a short and chubby man with big eyes and also Noko's mute cop partner. One of the career paths that Mashaba chooses is becoming a police detective. Mthembu has been featured on several episodes and all those episodes he has never said a single word. He only cares arresting the bad guys and going home. He doesn't speak too much, but when he does he makes sense. He has bad luck for being in the wrong place at the wrong time but luckily he has a friend \u2013 Noko Mashaba \u2013 who always comes to his rescue.\n\nMashaba was raised by his witch grandmother, who is not hard to miss because of her odd skin color and her impaired eye form. She graduated at Loying school before Phusu and obtained the same degree as him. She wears a pierced gold ring across her nose interior that illustrates her fearlessness. She also wears a black witch hat and a long maroon coat. '''Gogo Mashaba's''' age is not known but it is estimated to be in eons. She spent all her life \"eating and sleeping witchcraft\" that, over the eons she became the most feared and powerful sorcerer ever known. However, she became obsessed with testing her sorcery abilities that she ended up going to the mysterious mountain of Modimolle. She disappeared and is still missing.\n \n'''Donald Mashaba''' also known as Malome Dons (Pedi term for '''Uncle Dons''') is Noko's greedy and stubborn uncle who is also an example of many South African men that live life by the motto \u2013 mottoes such as \"you only live once\" or \"life is too short to use rubber\" etc. which is the reason why he is in a maintenance mess. Dons spends most of his time unemployed, but he does get employed, all his money goes to child support because he has 14 kids with 5 different mothers. Dons is also voiced by Lekganyane.\n\nBefore Mashaba could apply for any job he is obliged to first obtain his Matric certificate. '''Tjortan \"Slyfish\" Motaung''' is Noko Mashaba's  short tempered school teacher and the HOD of Maths & Science at the school. He holds a degree in applied mathematics and science. Mashaba and Motaung don't see eye to eye and since Motaung has a short temper & anger management issues, he sometimes gets carried away to a point of misconduct. He's made it his personal mission to get Noko suspended out of the school because he simply does not cooperate in class. Motaung is inspired by Lekganyane's late primary teacher.\n\nLastly, '''Mahlodi''' is Mashaba's high school sweetheart. She is a strong and independent woman who believes in equality between men and women in both the workplace and relationships. Mahlodi comes from a fairly wealthy family; she bails Noko out of bad situations almost every time. She uses that power to win gender equality arguments against Noko.\n\nThe series uses a few South African languages compromising Sepedi, iSiZulu, Setswana and English. It also uses small amounts of [[Fanagalo]] and an abundant mixture of street slang. Mashaba has popularized a few street slang words such as \"Abashwe\" or \"Habashwe\", which is originally known to the [[Tswana people]] and [[Pedi people]] as a sentence that means '''let them die'''. However, as a slang word, the term means '''Let's do this'''. The videos are intentionally in Jonas' home language, Sepedi.  The animated characters he grew up watching were always Western and English speaking and he feels it is important for young people to preserve their languages.\n\n==Origins and creation==\nRight after dropping out of [[University of Pretoria]] in 2013, Lekganyane began educating himself about two-dimensional animation using Google, Animation forums and YouTube tutorials. He then practiced drawing on a computer while developing his first animated visuals using [[Paint (software)|Windows Paint]] & [[Windows Movie Maker]]. A month later he had released his first animated video titled ''Night shift with Khaphela'' featuring a local soapie Generations' former actor Khaphela and a gigantic bee called Nthato. Soon after that Lekganyane created the first image of Noko Mashaba inspired by his close friend Soul Mashaba. At the time Noko Mashaba wore a green cap, with his Afro hidden inside and long brown shoes. The first episode that aired on [[YouTube]] was \"Noko & the famous Venda tree\", which was released on March 2013 then a few more episodes were released until the release of an episode called \"Noko & The spear\" - which followed the controversial issue about the [[South Africa]]n painting of the South African president [[Jacob Zuma]] called [[The Spear (painting)|''The Spear'']]. This is the episode where Noko's uncle was introduced as a crossover character. Uncle Dons later appeared in his own show called ''[[The Dons Show]]'' which premiered with a [[webisode]] called ''Jesus is back & black'' - an episode that was inspired by a true story that made the headlines about a man from [[KwaZulu-Natal|Kwa-Zulu-Natal]] who claimed to be the reincarnation of [[Jesus Christ]].\n\nIn 2014, Lekganyane released a high school themed series of episodes where Mashaba appeared as a misbehaving & reluctant high school student.\nThe first episode called ''Noko in high school'', followed by ''Noko vs Izikhothane'' reaching millions of YouTube users and mobile users across [[South Africa]], [[Botswana]] and other African countries. A sequel to the episode was released under the title ''Noko vs Izkikhothane Part 2'' which also went viral.\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\nInitial stages of the development of the each episode are conceptualizing, screenwriting, traditional hand-drawing & digital character rigging. All the scripts are written by Jonas Lekganyane with ideas inspired by his daily experiences and current affairs. He then sketches the characters on a piece of paper and scans them using a digital printer into a computer. When all the characters have been digitally rigged Lekganyane uses his cousins and friends for voice overs because when he started he could not afford to hire professional voice-over artists. Lekganyane's method of animation neglects other animation steps such as story-boarding and animatics. On completion of voice-over recording, Jonas animates the final product and lip syncs it with the voice-overs. The last stages of development include sound production, editing and subtitling. To avoid paying for copyrighted music and getting slammed with lawsuits, Lekganyane also produces the music and sound effects for the series.\n\n==Awards==\n{| class= \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Work\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2015\n| colspan=\"2\"|South Africa Film, Art, Music & Entertainment (FAME) awards\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n{| class= \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Work\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2016\n| colspan=\"2\"| YouTube Southern Africa Comics\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n* {{Cite web\n| title = Against All Odds - Jonas Lekganyane takes the world of youtube by storm\n| work = eNews Channel Africa\n| accessdate = 2014-07-17\n| date = 2014-01-16\n| url = http://www.enca.com/media/video/against-all-odds-jonas-lekganyane-takes-world-youtube-storm\n}}\n* {{Cite web\n| last = Thamsanqa Nsibanyoni\n| title = CONVERSATION WITH THE BRAINS BEHIND RAMS COMICS!\n| work = Soweto Magazine\n| accessdate = 2014-07-17\n| date = 2014-05-07\n| url = http://sowetomagazine.com/sm-feature-conversation-with-the-brains-behind-rams-comics/\n}}\n* {{Cite web\n| last = Maseo Nethanani\n| title = Meet the creator of Noko Mashaba\n| work = Capricorn Voice\n| accessdate = 2014-07-17\n| date = 2014-05-06\n| url = http://capricornreview.co.za/20578/meet-the-creator-of-noko-mashaba/\n}}\n\n* {{Cite web\n| last = Jonas Lekganyane\n| title = About the adventures of Noko Mashaba\n| work = Noko Mashaba website\n| accessdate = 2014-11-07\n| date = 2014-05-07\n| url = http://www.nokomashaba.co.za/about//\n}}\n\n* {{Cite web\n| title = 100% Youth 2 - Episode 6 :Jonas Lekganyane\n| work = SABC Education Shows\n| accessdate = 2014-11-07\n| date = 2014-10-23\n| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8PuuVtGmrHA&list=UUnHspqMx6eWIgCQfExI4Rdg\n}}\n\n* {{Cite web\n| last = Staff Writer\n| title = Google reveals most watched videos\n| work = iTwebs\n| accessdate = 2014-12-29\n| date = 2014-12-10\n| url = http://www.itweb.co.za/?id=139963:Google-reveals-most-watched-videos\n}}\n\n* {{Cite web\n| last = Mara Ispas\n| title = SA\u2019s 2014 Top Ten Trending YouTube Clips\n| work = ZA.yahoo news\n| accessdate = 2014-12-29\n| date = 2014-12-15\n| url = https://za.news.yahoo.com/watch-sa-2014-top-ten-trending-youtube-clips-113333245.html\n}}\n\n* {{Cite web\n| last = Staff Writer\n| title = Jonas 'Noko Mashaba'Lekganyane\n| work = www.polokwanecity.co.za\n| accessdate = 2015-05-14\n| date = 2014-12-15\n| url = http://www.polokwanecity.co.za/jonas-noko-mashaba-lekganyane/\n}}\n\n* {{Cite web\n| last = Staff Writer\n| title = Watch South Africa's top YouTube videos of 2015\n| work = www.timeslive.co.za\n| accessdate = 2015-12-21\n| date = 2015-12-10\n| url = http://www.timeslive.co.za/local/2015/12/10/Watch-South-Africas-top-YouTube-videos-of-2015\n}}\n\n* {{Cite web\n\n| title = Jonas Lekganyane : Cartoonist / Animation,\n| work = SABC Education\n| accessdate = 2014-09-30\n| date = 2014-08-16\t\n| url = http://www.sabceducation.co.za/100percentyouth/episodes/65-jonas-lekganyane-cartoonist-animation\n\t\n}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* {{Cite web\n| last = City Press\n| title = SA's favortite youtubers are...\n| work = www.channel24.co.za\n| accessdate = 2017-07-14\n| date = 2016-11-20\n| url = http://channel24.co.za/channel24/News/Local/sas-favourite-youtubers-are-20161119\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adventures of Noko Mashaba}}\n[[Category:South African animated television series]]\n[[Category:Animated web series]]\n[[Category:2010s animated television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South Africa animated sociopolitical satire}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox television\n| image                        =\n| caption                      = ''The Adventures of Noko Mashaba'' introduction shot, featuring all five of the main characters of the show.\n| genre                        = [[Satire]]<br />Black comedy<br />2D Animation<br />Adventure\n| creator                      = [[Jonas Lekganyane]]\n| runtime                      = 5 - 15 minutes\n| company                      = Rams Comics (Pty) Ltd.\n| executive_producer           = Jonas Lekganyane\n| voices                       = Katisho Mogashoa<br />Joey Lekganyane<br />Nash Maoasha<br />Jonas Lekganyane<br />Sbusiso Cossa<br />Sylvester Mphahlele\n|theme_music_composer          = [[Jonas Lekganyane]]\n|opentheme                     = \"[[The adventure of Noko Mashaba Theme|''The Adventures of Noko Mashaba'' Theme]]\"\n|country                       = [[South Africa]]\n|language                      = Sepedi<br />English<br />Zulu<br />Tswana\n| website                      = http://www.nokomashaba.co.za\n}}\n\n'''''The Adventures of Noko Mashaba''''' is a [[South Africa]]n animated sociopolitical satire created by a self-taught animator and university dropout [[Jonas Lekganyane]] for [[Soweto TV]], [[Ekurhuleni TV]] and [[YouTube]]. Intended for any audience, the show is inspired by the American adult animated sitcom ''[[South Park]]'' and centers around a fictional character \u2013 Noko Mashaba \u2013 an ordinary guy hailing from the calm streets of Limpopo, who occasionally ventures on extraordinary adventures to unravel mysteries and relive urban legends. On the show Mashaba always finds himself in informative, controversial and attention-grabbing situations.\n\nThe series was created in early 2013 and premiered on [[YouTube]] with one episode called \"Noko & the Famous Venda Tree\" \u2013 an episode about a mythological tree from the deep ends of [[Venda]], South Africa, which supposedly extends men's penises if planted in the right manner. The series first went viral over the internet after the release of the episode called \"Noko in High School\". The show focuses on current affairs, corruption, celebrity scandals, urban legends, history and random humor.\n\nLekganyane developed the series in 2013 after being obliged to drop out of varsity due to financial difficulties. After a few months he started his own animation company called [[Rams Comics]]. The production company that produces the adventures of Noko Mashaba and other cartoon shows such as [[The Dons show]].\n\nAn episode of the show called \"Noko vs. Izikhothane\" was rated as the most watched YouTube video of the year by [[Google]] when it revealed the most watched videos of the year in South Africa 2014. In 2015 two of the episodes of the show made their way to Google's Top 10 most viewed YouTube videos in South Africa. The show has made a number of features on a number of South African television shows. In early 2014 the show made its debut TV feature on an [[E.tv|ETV]] show called ''Against All Odds'' with Mpho Lakage, which was a profiling interview about the creator [[Jonas Lekganyane]], followed by ''[[Mzansi insider]]'', ''[[100% Youth]]'' and ''[[Sunday Live]]'' on [[SABC]]. In 2015 Noko Mashaba won the South African Film, Art, Music & Entertainment award (FAME) for best comedian. In 2016 Rams Comics along with ''[[Supa Strikas]]'' shared the comic category award of the [[YouTube]] Sub-Saharan Africa Creator YouTube awards.\n\n==Premise==\n\n===Setting and characters===\n\nThe series features characters inspired by people that exist in real life and famous [[South Africa]]n personalities. It starts with a disclaimer similar to ''[[South Park]]''{{'}}s [[tongue-in-cheek]] disclaimer: \"All characters and events in the following clip\u2014even those based on real people\u2014are entirely fictional. All celebrity voices are impersonated... Poorly.\"\n\nThe show follows the intriguing life of a fictional character, '''Noko Mashaba'''. Mashaba is an audacious chap, well known for his humorous personality, created and voiced by [[Jonas Lekganyane]]. Noko was raised by his grandmother; his parents were political activist in the [[South African apartheid]] era. They disappeared with other activists into exile before their son could speak. Noko is in between jobs, in some episodes he is a Barbershop owner, some he is the president's right-hand man, but most of the time he appears as a cop.\n\nMashaba always has a sidekick with him, one of his sidekicks is '''Phusu''' \u2013 an intellectual Sangoma/wizard, who graduated at a fictional university called \"Loying University\" and obtained a degree in \"Loying Engineering\". Phusu combines the art of sorcery and science to solve the unsolvable, which makes him a remarkably exceptional [[Traditional healers of South Africa|Sangoma]].\n\nMashaba's second sidekick is '''Mthembu''' - a short and chubby man with big eyes and also Noko's mute cop partner. One of the career paths that Mashaba chooses is becoming a police detective. Mthembu has been featured on several episodes and all those episodes he has never said a single word. He only cares arresting the bad guys and going home. He doesn't speak too much, but when he does he makes sense. He has bad luck for being in the wrong place at the wrong time but luckily he has a friend \u2013 Noko Mashaba \u2013 who always comes to his rescue.\n\nMashaba was raised by his witch grandmother, who is not hard to miss because of her odd skin color and her impaired eye form. She graduated at Loying school before Phusu and obtained the same degree as him. She wears a pierced gold ring across her nose interior that illustrates her fearlessness. She also wears a black witch hat and a long maroon coat. '''Gogo Mashaba's''' age is not known but it is estimated to be in eons. She spent all her life \"eating and sleeping witchcraft\" that, over the eons she became the most feared and powerful sorcerer ever known. However, she became obsessed with testing her sorcery abilities that she ended up going to the mysterious mountain of Modimolle. She disappeared and is still missing.\n \n'''Donald Mashaba''' also known as Malome Dons (Pedi term for '''Uncle Dons''') is Noko's greedy and stubborn uncle who is also an example of many South African men that live life by the motto \u2013 mottoes such as \"you only live once\" or \"life is too short to use rubber\" etc. which is the reason why he is in a maintenance mess. Dons spends most of his time unemployed, but he does get employed, all his money goes to child support because he has 14 kids with 5 different mothers. Dons is also voiced by Lekganyane.\n\nBefore Mashaba could apply for any job he is obliged to first obtain his Matric certificate. '''Tjortan \"Slyfish\" Motaung''' is Noko Mashaba's  short tempered school teacher and the HOD of Maths & Science at the school. He holds a degree in applied mathematics and science. Mashaba and Motaung don't see eye to eye and since Motaung has a short temper & anger management issues, he sometimes gets carried away to a point of misconduct. He's made it his personal mission to get Noko suspended out of the school because he simply does not cooperate in class. Motaung is inspired by Lekganyane's late primary teacher.\n\nLastly, '''Mahlodi''' is Mashaba's high school sweetheart. She is a strong and independent woman who believes in equality between men and women in both the workplace and relationships. Mahlodi comes from a fairly wealthy family; she bails Noko out of bad situations almost every time. She uses that power to win gender equality arguments against Noko.\n\nThe series uses a few South African languages compromising Sepedi, iSiZulu, Setswana and English. It also uses small amounts of [[Fanagalo]] and an abundant mixture of street slang. Mashaba has popularized a few street slang words such as \"Abashwe\" or \"Habashwe\", which is originally known to the [[Tswana people]] and [[Pedi people]] as a sentence that means '''let them die'''. However, as a slang word, the term means '''Let's do this'''. The videos are intentionally in Jonas' home language, Sepedi.  The animated characters he grew up watching were always Western and English speaking and he feels it is important for young people to preserve their languages.\n\n==Origins and creation==\nRight after dropping out of [[University of Pretoria]] in 2013, Lekganyane began educating himself about two-dimensional animation using Google, Animation forums and YouTube tutorials. He then practiced drawing on a computer while developing his first animated visuals using [[Paint (software)|Windows Paint]] & [[Windows Movie Maker]]. A month later he had released his first animated video titled ''Night shift with Khaphela'' featuring a local soapie Generations' former actor Khaphela and a gigantic bee called Nthato. Soon after that Lekganyane created the first image of Noko Mashaba inspired by his close friend Soul Mashaba. At the time Noko Mashaba wore a green cap, with his Afro hidden inside and long brown shoes. The first episode that aired on [[YouTube]] was \"Noko & the famous Venda tree\", which was released on March 2013 then a few more episodes were released until the release of an episode called \"Noko & The spear\" - which followed the controversial issue about the [[South Africa]]n painting of the South African president [[Jacob Zuma]] called [[The Spear (painting)|''The Spear'']]. This is the episode where Noko's uncle was introduced as a crossover character. Uncle Dons later appeared in his own show called ''[[The Dons Show]]'' which premiered with a [[webisode]] called ''Jesus is back & black'' - an episode that was inspired by a true story that made the headlines about a man from [[KwaZulu-Natal|Kwa-Zulu-Natal]] who claimed to be the reincarnation of [[Jesus Christ]].\n\nIn 2014, Lekganyane released a high school themed series of episodes where Mashaba appeared as a misbehaving & reluctant high school student.\nThe first episode called ''Noko in high school'', followed by ''Noko vs Izikhothane'' reaching millions of YouTube users and mobile users across [[South Africa]], [[Botswana]] and other African countries. A sequel to the episode was released under the title ''Noko vs Izkikhothane Part 2'' which also went viral.\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\nInitial stages of the development of the each episode are conceptualizing, screenwriting, traditional hand-drawing & digital character rigging. All the scripts are written by Jonas Lekganyane with ideas inspired by his daily experiences and current affairs. He then sketches the characters on a piece of paper and scans them using a digital printer into a computer. When all the characters have been digitally rigged Lekganyane uses his cousins and friends for voice overs because when he started he could not afford to hire professional voice-over artists. Lekganyane's method of animation neglects other animation steps such as story-boarding and animatics. On completion of voice-over recording, Jonas animates the final product and lip syncs it with the voice-overs. The last stages of development include sound production, editing and subtitling. To avoid paying for copyrighted music and getting slammed with lawsuits, Lekganyane also produces the music and sound effects for the series.\n\n==Awards==\n{| class= \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Work\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2015\n| colspan=\"2\"|South Africa Film, Art, Music & Entertainment (FAME) awards\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n{| class= \"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Work\n! Result\n! Ref.\n|-\n| 2016\n| colspan=\"2\"| YouTube Southern Africa Comics\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n* {{Cite web\n| title = Against All Odds - Jonas Lekganyane takes the world of youtube by storm\n| work = eNews Channel Africa\n| accessdate = 2014-07-17\n| date = 2014-01-16\n| url = http://www.enca.com/media/video/against-all-odds-jonas-lekganyane-takes-world-youtube-storm\n}}\n* {{Cite web\n| last = Thamsanqa Nsibanyoni\n| title = CONVERSATION WITH THE BRAINS BEHIND RAMS COMICS!\n| work = Soweto Magazine\n| accessdate = 2014-07-17\n| date = 2014-05-07\n| url = http://sowetomagazine.com/sm-feature-conversation-with-the-brains-behind-rams-comics/\n}}\n* {{Cite web\n| last = Maseo Nethanani\n| title = Meet the creator of Noko Mashaba\n| work = Capricorn Voice\n| accessdate = 2014-07-17\n| date = 2014-05-06\n| url = http://capricornreview.co.za/20578/meet-the-creator-of-noko-mashaba/\n}}\n\n* {{Cite web\n| last = Jonas Lekganyane\n| title = About the adventures of Noko Mashaba\n| work = Noko Mashaba website\n| accessdate = 2014-11-07\n| date = 2014-05-07\n| url = http://www.nokomashaba.co.za/about//\n}}\n\n* {{Cite web\n| title = 100% Youth 2 - Episode 6 :Jonas Lekganyane\n| work = SABC Education Shows\n| accessdate = 2014-11-07\n| date = 2014-10-23\n| url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8PuuVtGmrHA&list=UUnHspqMx6eWIgCQfExI4Rdg\n}}\n\n* {{Cite web\n| last = Staff Writer\n| title = Google reveals most watc