{"title_page": "Helena Slizynska", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Helena Slizynska''' (nee '''Gworek''') (Polish spelling Helena \u015ali\u017cy\u0144scy) (1908-1977) was a geneticist at the [[University of Edinburgh]] who conducted important work on the fruit fly ''[[Drosophila]]''.\n\n== Early life and career ==\nHelena Gworek was born in 1908 in Krak\u00f3w, Poland. She studied agriculture at the [[Jagiellonian University]] where Dr. [[:pl:Bronis\u0142aw \u015ali\u017cy\u0144ski|Bronis\u0142aw Marceli \u015ali\u017cy\u0144ski]] was a lecturer in genetics. The head of the Department at that time was Professor [[:pl:Teodor Marchlewski|Teodor Marchlewski]], who had previously worked as a researcher at the Institute of Animal Genetics in Edinburgh. Helena graduated with a thesis on selection in ''Drosophila''. In 1936 she married Slizynski and the couple received a grant from the [[Rockefeller Foundation]] which enabled them to go to [[Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory|Cold Spring Harbor]] for a year.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Auerbach|first=C.|date=May 1978|title=Helena Slizynska: 1908/1977|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/349371|journal=Mutation Research|volume=50|issue=2|pages=153\u2013156|doi=10.1016/0027-5107(78)90019-2|issn=0027-5107|pmid=349371}}</ref> Slyzinska worked together with [[Milislav Demerec]], using the new method for locating genes from overlapping deficiencies in the salivary gland chromosomes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Demerec|first=M.|last2=Slizynska|first2=H.|date=November 1937|title=Mottled White 258-18 of Drosophila Melanogaster|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17246869|journal=Genetics|volume=22|issue=6|pages=641\u2013649|issn=0016-6731|pmc=1208994|pmid=17246869}}</ref>\n\n== Career in Edinburgh ==\nIn August 1939, the Slizynskis came to Edinburgh to attend the Seventh International Congress of Genetics, which was being hosted by the Institute of Animal Genetics under [[Francis Albert Eley Crew]]. However, the outbreak of war during the Congress prevented the couple from returning to Poland and they remained permanently in Edinburgh. During the war Helena worked as senior assistant in the Department of Biology and Genetics at the [[Polish School of Medicine]] in Edinburgh. When the war ended she joined the Institute of Animal Genetics as a researcher.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2016-06-28|others=Nenadic, Stana, Davis, Gayle, other|title=Polish School of Medicine at the University of Edinburgh (1941-1949) : a case study in the transnational history of Polish wartime migration to Great Britain|url=http://hdl.handle.net/1842/31032|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Hermann Joseph Muller|Hermann J. Muller]], who was also staying at the Institute at the time, enrolled their cytological expertise in problems that occupied him, especially the behaviour of the ring chromosome at replication.\n\nFirst in collaboration with her husband, then by herself, Helena analyzed the salivary glands of the progeny of irradiated and chemically treated males, developing a technique that made the results as reliable as humanly possible.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Slizynska|first=H.|date=May 1938|title=Salivary Chromosome Analysis of the White-Facet Region of Drosophila Melanogaster|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17246888|journal=Genetics|volume=23|issue=3|pages=291\u2013299|issn=0016-6731|pmc=1209013|pmid=17246888}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Slizynski|first=B. M.|date=May 1938|title=Salivary Chromosome Studies of Lethals in Drosophila Melanogaster|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17246887|journal=Genetics|volume=23|issue=3|pages=283\u2013290|issn=0016-6731|pmc=1209012|pmid=17246887}}</ref>\n\nSlizynska's most notable contribution was her analysis of the difference between the spectra of chromosomal changes produced by X-rays on the one hand and chemicals on the other.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Slizynska|first=H.|date=July 1969|title=The progressive approximation, with storage, of the spectrum of TEM-induced chromosomal changes in Drosophila sperm to that found after irradation|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/5796938|journal=Mutation Research|volume=8|issue=1|pages=165\u2013175|doi=10.1016/0027-5107(69)90151-1|issn=0027-5107|pmid=5796938}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life and death ==\nThe couple kept in contact with the many other Poles who came to Scotland during the war. Up to her death Slizynska was involved in the social life of the Polish community.\n\nHelena retired early to coincide with her husband's retirement, although she found it difficult to give up her scientific research. The couple had acquired a cottage in the Trossachs and it was here that Slizynska died from a heart attack after having survived several severe attacks in hospital.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=May 1978|title=Helena Slizynska: 1908/1977|url=https://doi.org/10.1016/0027-5107(78)90019-2|journal=Mutation Research/Fundamental and Molecular Mechanisms of Mutagenesis|volume=50|issue=2|pages=153\u2013156|doi=10.1016/0027-5107(78)90019-2|issn=0027-5107}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Helena Slizynska''' (nee '''Gworek''') (Polish spelling Helena \u015ali\u017cy\u0144scy) (1908-1977) was a geneticist at the [[University of Edinburgh]] who conducted important work on the fruit fly ''[[Drosophila]]''.\n\n== Early life and career ==\nHelena Gworek was born in 1908 in Krak\u00f3w, Poland. She studied agriculture at the [[Jagiellonian University]] where Dr. [[:pl:Bronis\u0142aw \u015ali\u017cy\u0144ski|Bronis\u0142aw Marceli \u015ali\u017cy\u0144ski]] was a lecturer in genetics. The head of the Department at that time was Professor [[:pl:Teodor Marchlewski|Teodor Marchlewski]], who had previously worked as a researcher at the Institute of Animal Genetics in Edinburgh. Helena graduated with a thesis on selection in ''Drosophila''. In 1936 she married Slizynski and the couple received a grant from the [[Rockefeller Foundation]] which enabled them to go to to [[Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory|Cold Spring Harbor]] for a year.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Auerbach|first=C.|date=May 1978|title=Helena Slizynska: 1908/1977|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/349371|journal=Mutation Research|volume=50|issue=2|pages=153\u2013156|doi=10.1016/0027-5107(78)90019-2|issn=0027-5107|pmid=349371}}</ref> Slyzinska worked together with [[Milislav Demerec]], using the new method for locating genes from overlapping deficiencies in the salivary gland chromosomes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Demerec|first=M.|last2=Slizynska|first2=H.|date=November 1937|title=Mottled White 258-18 of Drosophila Melanogaster|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17246869|journal=Genetics|volume=22|issue=6|pages=641\u2013649|issn=0016-6731|pmc=1208994|pmid=17246869}}</ref>\n\n== Career in Edinburgh ==\nIn August 1939, the Slizynskis came to Edinburgh to attend the Seventh International Congress of Genetics, which was being hosted by the Institute of Animal Genetics under [[Francis Albert Eley Crew]]. However, the outbreak of war during the Congress prevented the couple from returning to Poland and they remained permanently in Edinburgh. During the war Helena worked as senior assistant in the Department of Biology and Genetics at the [[Polish School of Medicine]] in Edinburgh. When the war ended she joined the Institute of Animal Genetics as a researcher.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2016-06-28|others=Nenadic, Stana, Davis, Gayle, other|title=Polish School of Medicine at the University of Edinburgh (1941-1949) : a case study in the transnational history of Polish wartime migration to Great Britain|url=http://hdl.handle.net/1842/31032|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Hermann Joseph Muller|Hermann J. Muller]], who was also staying at the Institute at the time, enrolled their cytological expertise in problems that occupied him, especially the behaviour of the ring chromosome at replication.\n\nFirst in collaboration with her husband, then by herself, Helena analyzed the salivary glands of the progeny of irradiated and chemically treated males, developing a technique that made the results as reliable as humanly possible.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Slizynska|first=H.|date=May 1938|title=Salivary Chromosome Analysis of the White-Facet Region of Drosophila Melanogaster|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17246888|journal=Genetics|volume=23|issue=3|pages=291\u2013299|issn=0016-6731|pmc=1209013|pmid=17246888}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Slizynski|first=B. M.|date=May 1938|title=Salivary Chromosome Studies of Lethals in Drosophila Melanogaster|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17246887|journal=Genetics|volume=23|issue=3|pages=283\u2013290|issn=0016-6731|pmc=1209012|pmid=17246887}}</ref>\n\nSlizynska's most notable contribution was her analysis of the difference between the spectra of chromosomal changes produced by X-rays on the one hand and chemicals on the other.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Slizynska|first=H.|date=July 1969|title=The progressive approximation, with storage, of the spectrum of TEM-induced chromosomal changes in Drosophila sperm to that found after irradation|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/5796938|journal=Mutation Research|volume=8|issue=1|pages=165\u2013175|doi=10.1016/0027-5107(69)90151-1|issn=0027-5107|pmid=5796938}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life and death ==\nThe couple kept in contact with the many other Poles who came to Scotland during the war. Up to her death Slizynska was involved in the social life of the Polish community.\n\nHelena retired early to coincide with her husband's retirement, although she found it difficult to give up her scientific research. The couple had acquired a cottage in the Trossachs and it was here that Slizynska died from a heart attack after having survived several severe attacks in hospital.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=May 1978|title=Helena Slizynska: 1908/1977|url=https://doi.org/10.1016/0027-5107(78)90019-2|journal=Mutation Research/Fundamental and Molecular Mechanisms of Mutagenesis|volume=50|issue=2|pages=153\u2013156|doi=10.1016/0027-5107(78)90019-2|issn=0027-5107}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helena_Slizynska"}
{"title_page": "Savage (Megan Thee Stallion song)", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Savage (song)|2=Talk:Savage (Megan Thee Stallion song)#Requested move 26 March 2020 }}</noinclude>\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Savage\n| type       = single\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| artist     = [[Megan Thee Stallion]]\n| EP         = [[Suga (EP)|Suga]]\n| released   = April 7, 2020\n| format     = \n*[[Music download|Digital download]]\n*[[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   =\n| genre      = <!-- Please source genres -->\n| length     = {{duration|m=2|s=35}}\n| label      = 1501 Certified [[300 Entertainment|300]] ([[Warner Music Group|Warner]])\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Megan Thee Stallion|Megan Pete]]|[[J. White Did It|Anthony White]]|Bobby Session, Jr.}}\n| producer   = [[J. White Did It]]\n| prev_title = Freak\n| prev_year  = 2020\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       =\n}}\n\n\"'''Savage'''\" is a song by American rapper [[Megan Thee Stallion]]. It was released on March 6, 2020 as part of her EP ''[[Suga (EP)|Suga]]'' and later sent to US [[Contemporary hit radio|Top 40 radio]] formats on April 7, 2020 by 1501 Certified Entertainment and [[300 Entertainment]] as the third single from the EP.<ref name=\"AllAccess\">{{cite web|title=Top 40/M Future Releases|url=https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|website=All Access|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330200214/https://www.allaccess.com/top40-mainstream/future-releases|archivedate=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The song went viral on video-sharing app [[TikTok]], with people performing the \"Savage\" dance challenge during the song's chorus.\n\n==Recording==\nAccording to [[audio engineer|engineer]], Eddie \"eMIX\" Hernandez, Megan did the song \"on the spot\", in under an hour. Hernandez explained the recording process: \"The collaboration was going on at the same time. We were building as the song was forming. While he [producer [[J. White Did It]]] was laying down the [[snare drum|snares]] and the [[bass drum|kicks]], she was writing to the skeleton of the beat. Once he had the production all ready and sent it over to me, she was ready to go. She had all her writing done. Her recording?\u00a0She knocks them things out\".<ref name=\"eMix\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.revolt.tv/platform/amp/2020/3/6/21168229/megan-thee-stallion-suga-engineer-emix-interview|title=Studio Sessions - eMIX talks working with Megan Thee Stallion on 'Suga,' JT recording before her prison stint, Rick Ross and more|work=[[Revolt (TV network)|Revolt]]|last=Nelson Jr|first=Keith|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Compositon==\nCabdace McDuffie of ''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' noted, in the song, Megan \"paints herself as 'the [[ghetto|hood]] [[Mona Lisa]]' while celebrating her complexity\".<ref name=\"COS\" /> \nMegan employes huge bravado on the song, which, according to ''HipHopDX''{{'}}s Aaron McKrell, works to her advantage, as she \"surgically pummels a formidable [[J. White Did It]] beat into submission, and still makes time for cool quips like '''I need a mop to clean the floor, it's too much drip, ooh''{{'}}\".<ref name=\"HipHopDX\">{{Cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.3633/title.review-megan-thee-stallions-suga-fails-to-hit-the-sweet-spot|title=Review: Megan Thee Stallion's 'Suga' Fails To Hit The Sweet Spot|work=[[HipHopDX]]|last=McKrell|first=Aaron|date=March 23, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[Complex (magazine)|''Complex'']]'s Jessica McKinney said the beat is \"reminiscent of nostalgic hip-hop music videos set on a Miami beach, and its chorus is expressive, which is perfect for dancing\".<ref name=\"Complex\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/tiktok-songs-worth-listening-to/|title= 12 Songs Blowing Up on TikTok (That Are Actually Worth Listening to)|last=McKinney|first=Jessica|work=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n''[[Consequence of Sound]]'' named \"Savage\" as one of the essential tracks off [[Suga (EP)|''Suga'']].<ref name=\"COS\">{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2020/03/album-review-megan-thee-stallion-suga/|title=Megan Thee Stallion Hones Her Craft on the Suga EP|work=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=McDuffie|first=Candace|date=March 10, 2020|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> [[Complex (magazine)|''Complex'']]'s Jessica McKinney also named it a \"stand-out track\" from the EP.<ref name=\"Complex\" /> ''[[New York\u00a0(magazine)#Digital expansion and destination sites|Vulture]]'' commented that the song was \"joyfully conceited\", and that \"B.I.T.C.H.\" is a little lightweight as a first single when there's heat like 'Savage' on deck\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/megan-thee-stallon-suga-review-label-drama.html/|title=Why Shouldn't Megan Thee Stallion Take What's Hers?|work=Vulture|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Rob Sheffield of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' wrote that Megan is \"at her absolute peak\" and \"on top\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/megan-thee-stallion-suga-964567/|title=Megan Thee Stallion is at Her Peak on Suga|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Following its release, ''[[The Fader]]''{{'}}s Salvatore Maicki named \"Savage\" one of the \"10 songs you need in your life this week\", saying Megan checks all of the boxes [classy, [[Bourgeoisie|bougie]],\u00a0ratchet, sassy, moody,\u00a0AND\u00a0nasty] and \"sounds [[Cool (aesthetic)|fly]] as fuck while doing it\".<ref name=\"TheFader\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2020/03/12/new-songs-playlist-lil-uzi-megan-thee-stallion-yaeji-dixie-chicks/amp|title=10 songs you need in your life this week|work=[[The FADER]]|last=Maicki|first=Salvatore|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> [[Vice (magazine)|''Vice'']]'s Krstin Corry listed it as one of the best songs for the month of March 2020, asserting that \"with a [[hook (music)|hook]] that acknowledges all parts of her [Meghan's] identity, just like each of her EPs introduces a new persona, it's no wonder the world fell in love with it\".<ref name=\"Vice\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/pke4py/best-songs-march-2020|title=The 11 Songs We Couldn't Get Enough of This March|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|last=Corry|first=Kristin|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==TikTok challenge==\nThe \"Savage\" dance challenge was created by popular [[TikTok]] user Keara Wilson, whose viral clip racked up 15.7 million views and 2.4 million likes as of March 20, 2020.<ref name=\"Genius\">{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/megan-thee-stallion-s-savage-looks-poised-to-be-her-next-hit-thanks-to-this-viral-tiktok-challenge/|title=Megan Thee Stallion's \"Savage\" Looks Poised To Be Her Next Hit Thanks To This Viral TikTok Challenge|website=[[Genius (website)|Genius]]|last=Fu|first=Eddie|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Wilson posted her video for five days continuously, until it started going viral, and on March 16, Megan posted her own video, as well as videos of her fans and celebrities performing the challenge.<ref name=\"Oprah\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.oprahmag.com/entertainment/amp31932915/savage-challenge-megan-thee-stallion-lyrics/|title=Why You Can't Escape Megan Thee Stallion's \"Savage Challenge\" on TikTok|last=Jean-Phillipe|first=McKenzie|work=[[O, The Oprah Magazine|O magazine]]|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> The challenge involves people completing a \"quick and energetic\" choreographed dance.<ref name=\"Oprah\" />\n\n==Video==\nA Gracie Rothey-created lyric video premiered on April 7, 2020. It sees an animated\u00a0Keara Wilson doing the famous [[TikTok]] dance she created, as the lyrics pass through on screen.<ref name=\"Lyric Vid\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.revolt.tv/platform/amp/new-music/2020/4/7/21212369/megan-thee-stallion-savage-lyric-video|title=Megan Thee Stallion reveals lyric visual for \"Savage\"|website=[[Revolt (TV network)|Revolt]]|last=Powell|first=Jon|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=April 6, 2020|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n| 23\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|57|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|song=Savage|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|30|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|song=Savage|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia Tip|43|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|song=Savage|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 4, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|22|artist=Megan Thee Stallion|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Czechdigital|35|year=2020|week=14|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Estonia ([[Eesti Tipp-40]])<ref name=\"estonianchart\">{{Cite web|url=https://ekspress.delfi.ee/areen/eesti-tipp-40-muusikas-dua-lipa-keeras-the-weekndil-kaela-kahekorra?id=89479383|title=EESTI TIPP-40 MUUSIKAS: Dua Lipa keeras The Weekndil kaela kahekorra|language=Estonian|last=Nestor|first=Siim|website=[[Eesti Ekspress]]|date=April 7, 2020|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n| 16\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?semaine=14?&annee=2020&categorie=Top%20Singles|title=Top Singles (Week 14, 2020)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=April 7, 